{{Context|date=October 2009}} The '''Bakran tribe''' or Bagran tribe had connections with the [[Bagratuni Dynasty|Bagratuni Dynasty of Armenia]] and later [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and the [[Tirikan tribe]] with the [[Armenians|Armenian]] King [[Tigranes the Great]]. The reconstruction of [[Lake Van]] immediately east of the country of the Bakran tribe. This is the area [[Tigranes the Great|Tigrans]] family/clan was supposed to have dominated prior to its rise to the Armenian throne.<ref>Mehrdad R. Izady, ''The Kurds: A Concise Handbook'' (1992), Taylor & Francis, Washington, D.C., Page 91</ref>
The Bakran tribe has given its name to the city of [[Diyarbakır]], also engendered the Bagratid royal house, which ruled intermittently, first over the Armenians and later over the Georgians, with major interruptions from the 9th through the beginning of the 19th century. The original domain of the early Bagratids was in fact the area of Diyarbakır to [[Bingöl]] in northwest [[Kurdistan]], according to Tergewondian.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Kurds: a concise handbook|last= Mehrdad R. Izady|first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 1992|publisher= Taylor & Francis|location= |isbn= |page= |pages= 76–77|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=I9mr6OgLjBoC&pg=PA91&dq=Bakran+tribe&hl=en&ei=raOBTqSnB8qr-gaLqsncDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Bakran%20tribe&f=false|accessdate=}}</ref>
